_No response_

### Description

The guard only checks `if (!connection)`, but passes any truthy value through. Passing a plain object, a string, or an unrelated class instance causes confusing downstream errors when `connection.collection(...)` or `connection.models[...]` is accessed.

### Steps to Reproduce

```javascript
const Model = mongoose.model('Test', new Schema({ name: String }));
// Silently succeeds but corrupts state
Model.useConnection({ not: 'a connection' }); 
// Downstream error
try {
  await Model.findOne();
} catch (err) {
  console.log(err); // TypeError: connection.collection is not a function
}

### Expected Behavior

`Model.useConnection()` should throw a `TypeError` if the provided argument is not an instance of `mongoose.Connection`
